    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Discuss the following questions:"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulleted-list",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Imagine you lived in a poor neighborhood in one of the cities in this era. What would be hard about growing up in this environment? What are some opportunities that you might not have that middle-class residents would have?"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "What kinds of explanations for urban problems might have been offered by political liberals? What reforms do you think they might have proposed?"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "What kinds of explanations for urban problems might have been offered by political conservatives? What reforms do you think they might have proposed?"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Extension Activity: Ask students to read "
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/1978/03/28/archives/president-proposes-a-broad-new-policy-for-urban-recovery-fate-in.html",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "this "
            },
            {
              "text": "New York Times",
              "italic": true
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " summary of then-President Jimmy Carter’s proposal of a broad federal policy to address problems in American cities. Ask: Which of these proposals do you think would be effective in addressing those problems? Which would not be effective? What criticism might this proposal have faced?\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
